The same principles apply: clear hierarchy, consistent spacing, color restraint, legible type.

## The Transfer Test

After finishing any UI project, ask:
- Could this hierarchy work on a printed page?
- Would the spacing still make sense if I printed and cut this out?
- Does the color palette work without a backlit screen?

If yes to all three, you've learned good design, not just screen design.

## Quick Exercise

Print your current UI project at 100%. Pin it to a wall. Stand 2 meters back. Can you read the primary action and main headline without moving closer? If not, fix the hierarchy. Walk closer and check that secondary information makes sense. This takes 10 minutes and teaches you more than an hour tweaking on-screen.

## Quick Recap

- Physical design follows the same hierarchy, spacing, type, and color rules as screen.
- What changes: material costs, viewing conditions, fabrication constraints, tactile perception.
- The paper prototype process reveals problems no screen preview can.
- The same principles that make great UI make great posters, labels, and forms. The application changes, not the rules.
